{:proof/problem-id "apm-t99J03", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (goal and alignment explicitly reference compact connected triangulated surfaces, connected sums of tori/projective planes, and Euler characteristic) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the formal targets assert the classification rather than assume it) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (the stated theorems still express substantive mathematics on their own) · notes: Mathlib currently lacks these surface-classification theorems, so any Lean work will require upstream development.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Describe the connected-sum and Euler-characteristic classifications of compact connected triangulated surfaces and outline how the polygon-cutting proof produces them.\"\n :terms [{:name \"connected sum model\"\n          :meaning \"Every closed surface is built by connected sums of tori or of projective planes.\"\n          :needed-because \"Part (a) asks for this precise statement and the later parts rely on it.\"}\n         {:name \"orientability dichotomy\"\n          :meaning \"Each surface is either orientable (handlebody) or nonorientable (crosscap sum).\"\n          :needed-because \"The outline in part (b) splits into these two cases and the Euler characteristic formula depends on which case we are in.\"}\n         {:name \"Euler characteristic bookkeeping\"\n          :meaning \"χ detects the number of handles or crosscaps via χ = 2 − 2g or χ = 2 − k.\"\n          :needed-because \"Part (c) phrases the classification numerically, so we must track how χ behaves under connected sum.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Surface.classification_connected_sum\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Start from a triangulation, cut to obtain a polygon, and use edge pairings to read off handles or crosscaps.\"\n             :why-this-now \"This is the classical route to the classification and simultaneously answers parts (a) and (b).\"\n             :lean-target \"A Lean theorem stating that any compact connected triangulated 2-manifold is homeomorphic to a connected sum of g tori or k projective planes.\"\n             :mathlib-status \"No such theorem is currently exposed in Mathlib; implementing it would require the full surface classification project.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Surface.euler_characteristic_classification\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Combine χ(S#T) = χ(S)+χ(T)−2 with the connected-sum list to derive χ = 2−2g (orientable) and χ = 2−k (nonorientable).\"\n             :why-this-now \"This converts the structural classification into the Euler-characteristic statement demanded in part (c).\"\n             :lean-target \"A Lean corollary equating the Euler characteristic with the handle/crosscap count.\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Same blocker: Mathlib lacks the foundational classification, so this corollary is also unavailable.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"Every compact, connected, triangulated surface is homeomorphic to either a connected sum of g ≥ 0 tori or a connected sum of k ≥ 1 projective planes, with g and k unique, and χ determines which case occurs.\"\n              :formal-name \"surface_classification\"\n              :formal-target \"theorem surface_classification (S : Surface) (hS : CompactConnectedTriangulated S) : ∃! g, S ≃ₕ Σᵍ T² ∨ ∃! k, S ≃ₕ Σᵏ ℝP²\"\n              :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                             :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                             :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                             :notes \"States the connected-sum classification the prompt asks for and mentions χ implicitly via uniqueness.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"surface_classification\"\n               :formal-statement \"Formal connected-sum classification theorem for compact connected triangulated surfaces.\"\n               :informal-clause \"Part (a): every surface is a connected sum of tori or projective planes.\"\n               :role :main-theorem}\n              {:formal-name \"surface_classification_euler\"\n               :formal-statement \"Corollary: if S is orientable then χ(S)=2−2g and otherwise χ(S)=2−k.\"\n               :informal-clause \"Part (c): classification phrased via Euler characteristic.\"\n               :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n- Stage 1 now contains the full reader-facing solution—statement, polygon-cutting outline, Euler-characteristic formulas, and “what connects”—see `execute.md:1-33`.\n- Stage 2 lists the supporting lemmas (`fundamental_polygon`, `polygon_moves`, `orientability_dichotomy`, `Euler_additivity`) and ties them back to the two strategy items recorded in `proof-plan.edn`.\n- Stage 3 documents the Lean blocker: `Main.lean` remains boilerplate because Mathlib does not yet include a surface-classification theorem; the gap and required upstream work are detailed in `execute.md:27-33` and logged in `changelog.edn`.\n- Stage 4 explains how the informal write-up will hook into a future Lean statement once the Mathlib infrastructure exists.\n\nAll frame artifacts (`execute.md`, `proof-plan.edn`, `formal-alignment.edn`, and `changelog.edn`) are now populated per the instructions.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/T99J03/Apm_v2_t99J03_1775013445880", :frame/id "apm-v2-t99J03-1775013445880", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T03:17:25.906971Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.T99J03.Apm_v2_t99J03_1775013445880", :pro